Chapter 1. OpenSIPS nats_consumer Module

1.1. Overview

   The nats_consumer module turns OpenSIPS into a pull-mode NATS
   JetStream consumer. A dedicated module process subscribes to
   JetStream streams, populates a per-handle SHM ring, and exposes
   the messages to OpenSIPS routing scripts via nats_fetch() and
   nats_fetch_batch(). Acknowledgements (nats_ack(),
   nats_ack_next(), nats_ack_progress(), nats_nak(), nats_term())
   travel back to the consumer process over an IPC socket and are
   then relayed to NATS.

   nats_consumer is the receive-side counterpart to the two other
   OpenSIPS NATS modules:
     * event_nats — publishes OpenSIPS events and script payloads
       to NATS subjects, optionally via JetStream async publish.
     * cachedb_nats — exposes NATS Key-Value buckets through the
       OpenSIPS cachedb interface.
     * nats_consumer — pulls messages off JetStream streams and
       delivers them to routing scripts, with explicit ack and
       request/reply support.

   Handles are registered dynamically at runtime via the MI
   command nats_consumer_bind or the script function
   nats_consumer_bind() (called from startup_route). There are no
   bind-time modparams: the module loads with an empty registry
   and every consumer handle is added on demand. When declarative
   bind parameters are used, the registry is snapshotted to disk
   and rehydrated across restarts.

   The module shares the same nats.c connection pool as event_nats
   (via lib/nats/libnats_pool.so), so a single OpenSIPS instance
   consumes one NATS connection per worker regardless of which
   NATS modules are loaded.

1.1.1. Process Model and Failure Handling

   nats_consumer registers a single dedicated worker named [NATS
   consumer] whose only job is to drive the JetStream pull loop
   and hand messages to the SHM ring. Acks travel back over a
   Unix-domain IPC socket (nats_ack_ipc.c).

   If the consumer worker dies for any reason (signal, segfault,
   OOM kill) the OpenSIPS core treats it as a fatal child death
   and shuts the entire instance down — exactly the same path a
   SIP UDP receiver crash takes (signals.c:handle_sigs, SIGCHLD
   branch). There is no per-process auto-restart; the consumer is
   not registered with the OSS_PROC_SELFEXIT flag.

   Operationally this means the supervisor that runs OpenSIPS
   (systemd, Kubernetes, etc.) is responsible for restarting the
   whole OpenSIPS instance after a consumer death. Bound handles
   survive that restart only when declared via the bind parameter
   (see the modparam below); otherwise the registry must be
   repopulated by re-issuing nats_consumer_bind. In-flight
   messages whose ack didn't reach NATS before the restart will be
   re-delivered after ack_wait.

1.1.2. When you need this module / when you don't

   Load nats_consumer when:
     * you need explicit-ack JetStream pull-mode consumption from
       script (nats_fetch, nats_ack, nats_nak, nats_term,
       nats_ack_progress);
     * you need durable consumers with bounded redelivery or
       replay semantics (deliver_policy = by_start_seq);
     * you need synchronous request/reply with NATS as a transport
       (nats_request) from a non-request route;
     * you need fine-grained per-handle counters and a watchdog
       endpoint (nats_consumer_health).

   You don't need it when: plain fire-and-forget core-NATS
   subscription with event_route[] dispatch is sufficient — that
   path is handled by event_nats's subscribe modparam. The
   event_nats subscribe path has no script-visible ack, no durable
   consumer state, no replay, and no per-message flow control, but
   is also a much smaller config and one fewer dedicated process.
   If your handler can tolerate at-most-once-effective semantics
   from EVI dispatch, prefer that path.

1.2. Dependencies

1.2.1. OpenSIPS Modules

   Mandatory: at least one other NATS module that calls
   nats_pool_register() — typically event_nats — must be loaded
   before nats_consumer. The consumer module does not own the
   shared lib/nats pool's transport configuration; it consumes the
   connection set up by the registrant. Without a registrant, the
   consumer process aborts at child_init with “NATS pool: not
   registered (call nats_pool_register first)”. Recommended load
   order: event_nats first, nats_consumer second.

   When TLS is used to reach the NATS cluster, load tls_openssl
   before the first NATS module so the nats.c library defers
   OpenSSL lifecycle management to OpenSIPS.

   Once event_nats and nats_consumer are both loaded, they share
   one nats.c connection pool and do not contend for the same
   socket or subject space. cachedb_nats may also be loaded
   alongside; the same pool is shared three ways.

1.2.2. External Libraries

     * nats.c with the per-key KV TTL API (libnats.so) — the
       official C client library for NATS. This module uses the
       multi-subject filter and pull-consumer APIs, and all NATS
       modules link the shared lib/nats pool, which requires the
       per-key KV TTL API (kvStore_CreateStringWithTTL, nats.c PR
       #1000). An older libnats is detected at build time and the
       NATS modules are skipped with a clear message.
     * A JetStream-enabled NATS server (v2.9 or later).

1.3. Exported Parameters

1.3.1. bind (string, multiple)

   Declarative handle bind. Each value uses the same
   key=value;key=value config grammar as nats_consumer_bind() and
   is bound into the registry at module init, before any worker
   forks. The parameter may be set multiple times, one handle per
   value.

   A malformed value, an unknown key, or a duplicate id is a
   configuration error and aborts startup. Handles bound at
   runtime through the MI command remain available but are
   ephemeral: after a restart only bind-declared handles exist.
   (The former persist_handles / persist_path file-snapshot
   mechanism was removed in favour of this parameter.)

   Example 1.1. Declare handles in the configuration
...
modparam("nats_consumer", "bind",
    "id=jobs;stream=JOBS;subject=jobs.>;durable=jobs_worker")
modparam("nats_consumer", "bind",
    "id=audit;stream=AUDIT;subject=audit.>")
...

1.3.2. fetch_batch (integer)

   Module-global default for the JetStream pull-Fetch batch size
   used by the dedicated consumer process when calling
   natsSubscription_Fetch. Each handle may override this with a
   per-handle fetch_batch= bind key.

   Range: 1..4096. Larger batches reduce the number of pull
   requests the consumer process issues against the broker (lower
   pulls_requested in MI counters, lower broker CPU per consumer).
   The consumer process clamps the request to the ring's
   currently-free slot count before each natsSubscription_Fetch
   call, so a fetch_batch that exceeds the worker's transient
   drain rate no longer triggers ring-full defer-drops; the broker
   simply holds the un-fetched messages until the next loop
   iteration. Pair with a generous ring_capacity (>= 4 *
   fetch_batch is the recommended ratio) and max_ack_pending (>=
   ring_capacity) so the clamp has room to deliver full batches.

   The drain pattern in the script matters more than this knob
   alone. Reference numbers, single-instance aarch64 loopback at
   N=100 000:
     * nats_fetch+nats_ack per-message: ~2 000 msgs/sec, gated by
       the OpenSIPS script-interpreter overhead.
     * nats_fetch_batch +nats_batch_select +nats_ack at
       fetch_batch=10: ~9 800 msgs/sec.
     * Same pattern at fetch_batch=64: ~37 500 msgs/sec.
     * Same pattern at fetch_batch=256: ~89 000 msgs/sec.

   See the README's "Choosing a drain pattern" and "Tuning
   fetch_batch" sections for the full trade-off matrix. At very
   high batches (>= 256) the broker's max_ack_pending becomes the
   next bottleneck; raising it (with ring_capacity raised to
   match) lifts the ceiling further at the cost of broker memory.

   Default value: 10

   Example 1.2. High-throughput durable -- override fetch_batch +
   ring
modparam("nats_consumer", "fetch_batch", 32)

# Per-handle override: throughput-bound durable wants 256 per Fetch
# with a 4x ring and a >= ring max_ack_pending.  Empirical
# ~89 000 msgs/sec on loopback at this configuration.
nats_consumer_bind("id=ingest;stream=EVENTS;durable=ingest;
  fetch_batch=256;ring_capacity=1024;max_ack_pending=4096");

1.3.3. fetch_timeout_ms (integer)

   Module-global default for the per-Fetch upper-bound wait, in
   milliseconds. Each handle may override this with a per-handle
   fetch_timeout_ms= bind key.

   Range: 1..60000 (1 ms .. 60 s). Lower values reduce shutdown
   latency (the consumer process polls this timeout between
   checking for retire/shutdown signals) at the cost of more
   wakeups on quiet streams. Higher values reduce idle CPU on
   streams that rarely have messages, at the cost of slower
   shutdown.

   Default value: 1000

   Example 1.3. Latency-sensitive RPC handle, short timeout
modparam("nats_consumer", "fetch_timeout_ms", 1000)

# RPC responder: stays responsive at shutdown by polling more often.
nats_consumer_bind("id=rpc;stream=API;durable=rpc;
  fetch_batch=4;fetch_timeout_ms=100");

1.3.4. poison_max_deliver (integer)

   Consumer-side poison-message cap. With the JetStream default
   max_deliver=0 the broker redelivers a message that always fails
   processing forever, broker-paced, with no dead-letter -- a
   single poison message can wedge a handle indefinitely. When
   this is greater than 0, the dedicated consumer process
   terminates (natsMsg_Term) any message whose NumDelivered
   exceeds the cap, instead of pushing it to the worker ring, and
   bumps the per-handle poisoned counter (visible in
   nats_consumer_list and nats_consumer_stats).

   This is a global backstop independent of any per-handle
   max_deliver= bind key: where a handle sets its own max_deliver
   the broker terminates first and the cap never fires. It exists
   mainly to bound redelivery for handles left at the unlimited
   default.

   Default value: 20. Set to 0 to disable the backstop (unlimited
   broker-paced redelivery).

   Example 1.4. Dead-letter a message after 20 failed deliveries
modparam("nats_consumer", "poison_max_deliver", 20)

1.3.5.  allow_sync_anywhere (integer)

   Opt-in switch that widens the route mask of the synchronous
   nats_request entry point so it may be called from SIP-worker
   contexts (REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE, BRANCH_ROUTE,
   ERROR_ROUTE). When unset (the default), the OpenSIPS parser
   rejects any call to bare nats_request from those routes with
   the diagnostic “Command <nats_request> cannot be used in the
   block”; only STARTUP_ROUTE, TIMER_ROUTE, LOCAL_ROUTE,
   EVENT_ROUTE, and ONREPLY_ROUTE remain accepted.

   The guard exists because natsConnection_RequestMsg blocks the
   calling worker for up to timeout_ms. A SIP UDP/TCP worker that
   blocks on the RPC cannot read its next packet for that long,
   which on a production proxy with a steady inbound rate quickly
   stalls SIP throughput. Operators who know their deployment can
   absorb the worst case (low RPS, a thin SIP gateway in front,
   generous worker pool sizing) may opt in to the simpler
   synchronous ergonomics by setting this to 1; the setter
   callback widens the nats_request entry's flag word to
   ALL_ROUTES at the moment the modparam directive is parsed,
   before any route block is checked.

   Per-route blocking consequences. Each of the newly-opened
   routes has its own distinct operational blast radius (verified
   against the core invocation paths cited below). The setter
   callback emits an LM_WARN at config-parse time spelling these
   out so an operator who flips the switch cannot miss them:
     * REQUEST_ROUTE. Runs on the SIP worker that received the
       request (receive.c:
       run_top_route(sroutes->request[DEFAULT_RT])). The worker
       cannot read its next SIP packet for the duration; under
       sustained load the recv backlog grows on this worker's
       interface.
     * FAILURE_ROUTE. Has two invocation paths with different
       blast radius and different async support:
          + Negative-reply trigger -- when an upstream branch
            returns a final non-2xx, the SIP worker that received
            the reply runs the failure route inline
            (modules/tm/t_reply.c: run_failure_handlers). Blast
            radius identical to REQUEST_ROUTE blocking on that
            worker; async() IS available from this trigger path
            because a SIP worker has a full reactor.
          + fr_timer / fr_inv_timer expiry -- the failure route
            runs inline on the timer ticker process, which is the
            single-threaded process forked by
            start_timer_processes in timer.c (loop body:
            run_timer_process, a bare select(0,0,0,0,&tv) tick
            driver with no reactor). This process exists solely to
            fire the C-level callbacks registered via
            register_timer() -- including TM's
            final_response_handler, which in turn calls fake_reply
            -> relay_reply -> run_failure_handlers inline.
            Blocking it queues every other transaction's fr_timer
            fire, every other module's tick callback
            (retransmissions, watchdogs, etc.) until the block
            clears. Worse blast radius than blocking a single SIP
            worker, and async() is not available from this trigger
            path because the ticker has no reactor -- there is no
            non-blocking option in this module for
            fr_timer-triggered failure_route today.
     * BRANCH_ROUTE. Runs on the SIP worker that is fanning out
       the transaction's outbound branches (modules/tm/t_fwd.c:
       pre_print_uac_request). The per-branch INVITE/REGISTER send
       is delayed by up to timeout_ms; subsequent branches in the
       same transaction also wait.
     * ERROR_ROUTE. Runs on the SIP worker that hit a parse error
       on an inbound request (receive.c) or that tripped an
       in-action error (action.c: run_error_route). Blocking
       delays the error response back to the peer.

   Note: timer_route { ... } blocks (not to be confused with the
   C-level register_timer() callbacks described under
   FAILURE_ROUTE above) execute on a separate Timer handler
   process that has a full reactor and supports async(). Calls to
   bare nats_request from timer_route are accepted by the default
   mask (TIMER_ROUTE is in the safe allow-list) and async() works
   there too. The ticker-process limitation discussed under
   FAILURE_ROUTE / fr_timer is a different process and a different
   code path.

   The recommended pattern for any worker route is the async form,
   which yields on a per-call eventfd while the reply is in flight
   and does not block SIP processing:
async(nats_request(subj, payload, tmo), reply_route)

   The async form is accepted from every route that supports
   async() regardless of this modparam -- request_route,
   branch_route, error_route, timer_route, event_route,
   onreply_route, and the reply-triggered branch of failure_route.
   The only worker-blocking situation without a non-blocking
   alternative is failure_route entered through fr_timer /
   fr_inv_timer expiry; lifting that requires an upstream change
   in tm that dispatches fr_timer expiry through a Timer handler
   instead of running it inline on the ticker. See nats_request
   below.

   Range: 0 (default, safer) or 1 (opt-in, permissive). Any other
   value is rejected at config-parse time so a typo cannot
   silently disarm the guard.

   Default value: 0

   Example 1.5. Opt in -- low-RPS deployment that prefers sync
   ergonomics
modparam("nats_consumer", "allow_sync_anywhere", 1)

route {
    # Operator has accepted that this call blocks the worker
    # for up to 200 ms; udp_workers sized accordingly.
    nats_request("rpc.lookup", $var(payload), 200);
    if ($retcode == 1) {
        xlog("got reply: $nats_data()\n");
    }
}

   Example 1.6. Default -- async from request_route, sync only in
   startup
# No modparam set; the default (0) keeps the safety guard in place.

startup_route {
    # Allowed -- no SIP worker is being stalled.
    nats_request("rpc.health", "ping", 1000);
}

route {
    # Async form -- worker yields to the reactor while the
    # RPC is in flight.  Accepted regardless of the modparam.
    async(nats_request("rpc.lookup", $var(payload), 200), got_reply);
}
route[got_reply] {
    if ($retcode == 1) {
        xlog("got reply: $nats_data()\n");
    }
}

1.3.6.  request_id_header (string)

   Outbound header name used to carry the per-call UUIDv7
   correlation id auto- minted by both the sync and async
   nats_request start paths. The id is also exposed to the script
   via the $nats_request_id pvar and persists across an async()
   yield so the resume route can read it back for log / trace
   correlation.

   Per-call cost. One clock_gettime(CLOCK_REALTIME) + one
   getrandom(GRND_NONBLOCK) of 10 bytes per request, plus a
   36-byte snprintf. Measured at roughly 200 ns on aarch64; below
   the noise floor of the libnats round-trip.

   UUIDv7 layout. RFC 9562 §5.7 lexicographically-sortable Type-7
   UUID: 48-bit unix milliseconds, 4-bit version (7), 12 random
   bits, 2 variant bits (10b), 62 random bits. Globally unique
   across instances and time; grep-able as one string from
   OpenSIPS logs through the NATS subject to the responder's logs.

   Auto-stage behaviour. When the modparam is non-empty, every
   nats_request call stages <header-name>: <uuid> onto the
   outbound natsMsg iff the script has not already staged the same
   header explicitly via nats_hdr_set. A deliberate
nats_hdr_set("X-Request-Id", "my-custom-id");
nats_request("rpc.x", "...", 200);

   wins -- the auto-stage observes the existing entry and steps
   aside.

   Disabling the header. Setting the modparam to the empty string
   ("") suppresses the auto-stage without affecting the mint: the
   id is still generated and the $nats_request_id pvar still
   works, but no header is added to the outbound msg. Use this
   when you want client-side correlation but the responder cannot
   accept (or will reject) the extra header.

   Range: any string that is a valid NATS header name. Common
   choices include X-Request-Id, Request-Id, X-Correlation-Id, or
   a vendor-prefixed X-MyOrg-Request-Id.

   Default value: "X-Request-Id"

   Example 1.7. End-to-end correlation: script -- broker --
   responder
modparam("nats_consumer", "request_id_header", "X-Request-Id")

route {
    xlog("L_INFO", "issuing rpc id=$nats_request_id\n");
    async(nats_request("rpc.lookup", $var(payload), 200), on_reply);
}

route[on_reply] {
    if ($retcode == 1) {
        # Responder echoed the header back -- verify it matches
        # what we issued (a responder that does not echo means
        # the operator has to grep their logs by the outgoing id
        # only).
        if ($nats_hdr(X-Request-Id) == $nats_request_id) {
            xlog("L_INFO", "rpc id=$nats_request_id ok: $nats_data()\n")
;
        } else {
            xlog("L_WARN", "rpc id=$nats_request_id reply id mismatch\n"
);
        }
    } else if ($retcode == -1) {
        xlog("L_WARN", "rpc id=$nats_request_id timed out\n");
    }
}

   Example 1.8. Vendor-prefixed header for a specific responder
   service
modparam("nats_consumer", "request_id_header", "X-MyOrg-Trace-Id")

   Example 1.9. Mint id locally but do not put it on the wire
modparam("nats_consumer", "request_id_header", "")

route {
    # $nats_request_id still has the UUIDv7, log it locally,
    # but the outbound natsMsg carries no Request-Id header.
    xlog("L_INFO", "rpc id=$nats_request_id (header suppressed)\n");
    async(nats_request("rpc.x", $var(payload), 200), on_reply);
}

1.3.7. NATS transport parameters (owned by event_nats)

   Connection-level NATS parameters (nats_url, reconnect_wait,
   max_reconnect, nats_drain_timeout_ms) are owned by event_nats
   and read through the shared lib/nats connection pool. Set them
   on the event_nats module; the consumer reuses the pool
   directly.

   TLS configuration is sourced from the tls_mgm client domain
   named "nats" at connect time — see the event_nats admin guide
   "TLS configuration" section for the canonical pattern.
   nats_consumer declares tls_mgm as DEP_SILENT, so plaintext-only
   deployments don't need it.

1.3.8. async_rpc_slots (integer)

   Size of the SHM slot pool that backs in-flight async
   nats_request() calls across all SIP workers. Each concurrent
   async RPC occupies one slot for its lifetime; when the pool is
   exhausted a new call fails (-5) and the script can retry or
   shed load. Clamped to the range 1..65536.

   Default value is “64”.

1.3.9. async_rpc_poll_ms (integer)

   Tick interval, in milliseconds, of the per-call worker-private
   guard timerfd behind an async nats_request(). The reply itself
   does not wait for this timer: the consumer process signals the
   calling worker over OpenSIPS IPC the moment the reply is
   delivered (or the call is abandoned), so the resume runs at
   wire latency. The guard tick only bounds how quickly a request
   timeout - or a lost wake signal - is noticed; the value is
   clamped to the range 1..1000.

   Default value is “100” (milliseconds).

1.3.10. reconnect_wait_ms (integer)

   Delay, in milliseconds, between reconnect attempts for the
   consumer process's connection to the broker. A value of 0 uses
   the shared lib/nats pool default. Other connection-level
   parameters are owned by event_nats (see nats_transport above).

   Default value is “0” (use the pool default).

1.4. Exported Functions

1.4.1.  nats_fetch(id, [timeout_ms])

   Pull a single JetStream message for the handle id off the SHM
   ring. Populates the per-worker $nats_* pseudo-variables with
   the delivered message's subject, data, sequence, delivery
   count, pending count, reply subject, and headers. Does not
   acknowledge the message — call nats_ack(), nats_nak(), or
   nats_term() explicitly.
     * id (string) — a previously- bound consumer handle id.
     * timeout_ms (integer, optional) — block up to this many
       milliseconds waiting for a message. Default 0 =
       non-blocking.

   Return values (no path returns 0 — a 0 return from a
   script-callable cmd terminates the calling route via
   ACT_FL_EXIT): 1 on success, -1 when no message arrived within
   the budget (not an error; script may retry), -2 when the
   underlying NATS connection is down (the consumer process
   surfaces this so scripts can distinguish transport failure from
   empty ring; call nats_last_error() for the human string), -3
   when the handle id is not found or is retiring, -6 on internal
   error.

   Also exported as an async command; see Section 1.4.2, “ async
   nats_fetch(id, [timeout_ms]) ”.

1.4.2.  async nats_fetch(id, [timeout_ms])

   Non-blocking variant of nats_fetch() for use inside async(...)
   launcher statements. The worker yields immediately after the
   call; a worker-private timerfd registered with the reactor
   polls the ring on each tick and resumes the worker when a
   message arrives, or once the per-call timeout_ms deadline
   expires.

   Example 1.10. Async fetch + ack in a request route
route[PROCESS] {
    async(nats_fetch("orders", 5000), ON_MSG);
}

route[ON_MSG] {
    if ($retcode == 1) {
        xlog("L_INFO", "got $nats_subject: $nats_data\n");
        nats_ack();
    } else {
        xlog("L_WARN", "no message, rc=$retcode\n");
    }
}

1.4.3.  nats_fetch_batch(id, [opts])

   Drain up to count messages in a single call. The fetched
   messages are staged in a per-worker batch buffer. Use
   nats_batch_select(i) to activate each one, then ack / nak /
   term it before moving on.

   opts is a semicolon-separated k=v string recognizing count
   (default 1), expires (duration, default 0 = non-blocking;
   accepts a bare integer interpreted as ms, or a suffix of ms / s
   / m / h / d), expires_ms (alias for expires; bare integer ms),
   and no_wait (bool, default 0).

   Returns the number of messages staged in $retcode, or a
   negative error code identical to nats_fetch(). The OpenSIPS
   script does not allow direct assignment of a function return to
   a $var(); capture $retcode immediately after the call.

   When expires is positive, the call blocks on the cross-process
   ring futex (nats_ring_wait) in slices of up to 100 ms until the
   requested count is reached or the deadline expires. This wait
   is bounded by the worker's request-route processing budget; do
   not set expires longer than the request a route is meant to
   take.

   Example 1.11. High-throughput batch drain pattern
timer_route[drain, 1] {
    $var(b) = 0;
    while ($var(b) < 5000) {
        nats_fetch_batch("jobs", "count=10;expires_ms=100");
        $var(rc) = $retcode;
        if ($var(rc) <= 0) { break; }
        $var(i) = 0;
        while ($var(i) < $var(rc)) {
            nats_batch_select($var(i));
            nats_ack();
            $var(i) = $var(i) + 1;
        }
        $var(b) = $var(b) + 1;
    }
}

1.4.4.  nats_batch_select(idx)

   Activate the idx-th message in the worker's current batch so
   subsequent $nats_* reads and nats_ack() / nats_nak() /
   nats_term() calls target it. Valid indices are 0 .. n-1 where n
   is the return of the most recent nats_fetch_batch(). Calling
   nats_batch_select() twice with the same index after
   acknowledging is a no-op and returns -1.

1.4.5.  Acknowledgement functions

     * nats_ack() — acknowledge the current message successfully.
     * nats_ack_next() — ack the current message and immediately
       request another delivery (reduces round-trips when
       tight-looping a durable consumer).
     * nats_ack_progress() — refresh the broker's ack timer
       without terminating the delivery. Use when a handler must
       exceed the handle's ack_wait without triggering a
       redelivery.
     * nats_nak() — negative-ack the current message; the broker
       schedules redelivery using the consumer's ack_wait.
     * nats_nak_delay(delay_ms) — same as nats_nak() but the
       broker schedules redelivery for delay_ms milliseconds in
       the future instead of using the consumer's ack_wait.
     * nats_term() — terminate the delivery with no retry.
       max_deliver-style advisory semantics still apply on the
       server side.
     * nats_in_progress() — like nats_ack_progress(), refresh the
       broker's ack timer to keep the current delivery alive past
       ack_wait, but without clearing the worker's current-message
       state. Subsequent nats_ack() / nats_nak() / nats_term()
       calls still target the same delivery. Use when a long
       handler will continue to poll progress and eventually
       finalise with one of the standard acks.

   All seven return 1 on success or -1 when there is no current
   message (or the worker's ack token has already been consumed).

1.4.6.  nats_hdr_set(name, value)

   Stage a header on the worker-local outgoing header buffer. The
   next nats_reply() or nats_request() flushes the staged headers
   onto the outbound NATS message. Up to 16 headers can be staged
   per worker; attempts to add more return -1.

   Staged headers are cleared after every nats_reply() or
   nats_request() regardless of outcome.

1.4.7.  nats_reply(payload)

   Publish payload to the current message's reply_to subject.
   Useful as the responder side of a request/reply exchange.
   Returns 1 on success, -1 when there is no current message, no
   reply_to, or the publish failed.

1.4.8.  nats_request(subject, payload, timeout_ms)

   NATS request/reply. Publishes payload to subject and waits for
   a reply on a per-call inbox. Two call shapes:
     * Sync:
nats_request("rpc.x", $var(p), 200);
       Blocks the calling worker for up to timeout_ms
       milliseconds. Default route mask permits STARTUP_ROUTE,
       TIMER_ROUTE, LOCAL_ROUTE, EVENT_ROUTE, ONREPLY_ROUTE only;
       request_route / failure_route / branch_route / error_route
       are reachable only after setting allow_sync_anywhere=1.
     * Async:
async(nats_request("rpc.x", $var(p), 200), on_reply);
       Yields the worker to the reactor on a per-call eventfd. A
       libnats subscription thread receives the reply on the
       worker's persistent inbox subscription and signals the
       eventfd; the resume route runs with the per-worker
       current-message state populated.

   On success the reply populates the script-visible state:
   $nats_data, $nats_subject, $nats_hdr(Name), $nats_reply_to. The
   $nats_request_id pvar holds the UUIDv7 used as the correlation
   id and is also staged as the X-Request-Id outbound header
   (modparam-configurable; can be overridden by the script).

   Return codes. No path returns 0 -- a 0 return from a
   script-callable cmd sets ACT_FL_EXIT in run_action_list
   (action.c:196) and silently terminates the calling route, which
   is never correct for an RPC result. Every outcome is therefore
   a positive success code or a negative error / non-result code:
     * 1 — reply delivered.
     * -1 — timeout: the broker is still reachable but the
       responder did not reply within timeout_ms. Script may retry
       with a longer timeout.
     * -2 — connection lost mid-flight. Async only. The pool
       reconnect epoch advanced or nats_pool_is_connected went
       false during the call. This is distinct from a timeout: the
       script should treat -2 as broker-down (alert,
       circuit-break, surface 503) rather than
       retry-with-longer-tmo.
       Latency note. The resume function checks the connection
       epoch on every guard tick, so a mid-flight disconnect
       surfaces -2 on the next guard tick -- worst case one
       async_rpc_poll_ms interval (100 ms default) after the pool
       notices the loss, independent of the script's timeout_ms. A
       reply that is already being delivered when the disconnect
       is detected still wins: the cancel uses the same atomic
       claim as the timeout path and backs off if the consumer got
       there first.
     * -3 — NATS unavailable at issue time (no pool connection).
       Returned before any publish attempt; the script can
       short-circuit without paying the timeout_ms wait.
     * -4 — request error (subject empty / too long, msg create
       failed, publish or sync-request failed).
     * -5 — per-worker in-flight cap reached. Async only. Default
       cap is 4096 simultaneous in-flight calls per worker;
       callers should implement back-pressure when this surfaces.
     * -6 — internal error (oom, format failure, missing eventfd,
       etc.).

   Example 1.12. Async request with full error-branch handling
route {
    async(nats_request("rpc.lookup", $var(payload), 200), on_reply);
}

route[on_reply] {
    if ($retcode == 1) {
        # success: reply in $nats_data
    } else if ($retcode == -1) {
        # timeout: responder slow; maybe retry with longer tmo
        xlog("L_WARN", "rpc id=$nats_request_id timeout\n");
    } else if ($retcode == -2) {
        # broker is down: alert / circuit-break
        xlog("L_ERR", "rpc id=$nats_request_id connection lost\n");
        sl_send_reply(503, "Service Unavailable");
    } else {
        # -3 / -4 / -5 / -6: configuration / publish / capacity / intern
al
        xlog("L_ERR", "rpc id=$nats_request_id failed rc=$retcode\n");
        sl_send_reply(500, "Internal Server Error");
    }
}

1.5. Exported Pseudo-Variables

     * $nats_subject — NATS subject the current message was
       delivered on.
     * $nats_data — message payload.
     * $nats_reply_to — reply subject (empty string when the
       publisher did not request a reply).
     * $nats_seq — JetStream stream sequence number.
     * $nats_consumer_seq — JetStream consumer-side sequence
       number.
     * $nats_delivered — broker's delivered counter (1 on first
       delivery, bumps on each redelivery).
     * $nats_pending — broker's estimate of messages still waiting
       on the stream after this one.
     * $nats_token — opaque ack token encoding (handle_idx,
       slot_idx, generation).
     * $nats_hdr(Name) — read a header from the current message.
       Lookup is case-insensitive. Name must be a literal; dynamic
       $nats_hdr($var(x)) forms are not supported.
     * $nats_request_id (read/write) — UUIDv7 correlation id of
       the most recent nats_request issued by this worker. Minted
       automatically by both the sync and async start paths at
       call time and stashed in per-worker process memory so it is
       readable before the call returns (sync), across the async()
       yield, and inside the resume route. Returns NULL on workers
       that have not yet issued any nats_request call and have no
       pending script assignment.
       Same value is auto-staged as the X-Request-Id outbound
       header (header name configurable via the request_id_header
       modparam); responders that echo the header on the reply get
       end-to-end correlation across logs and traces. Set the
       modparam to an empty string to mint but not stage.
       Caller-set override. Assigning to the pvar before a
       nats_request call swaps the auto-minted UUIDv7 for the
       script-supplied value on that one call (consume-once
       semantics): subsequent calls with no further assignment
       revert to minting fresh. Useful for propagating an inbound
       trace id (e.g. from a SIP header, an upstream tracing
       context, or a callee-specific correlation token) into the
       NATS request so the entire trace shares one id end-to-end.
       Validation: 1..63 bytes, no CR/LF (would inject
       pseudo-headers into the NATS wire format). Out-of-range
       assignments are rejected, an LM_WARN is logged explaining
       why, and the next call falls back to minting a fresh
       UUIDv7.
       Clearing the override. Both $nats_request_id = NULL and
       $nats_request_id = "" clear the pending override and the
       stash. The NULL form is handled by the pvar setter's
       early-return fast path; the empty-string form falls through
       to the same clear routine via the len <= 0 branch. After a
       clear, $nats_request_id reads NULL until the next
       nats_request mints fresh.
       Example 1.13. Correlate an async RPC across log lines
route {
    xlog("L_INFO", "issuing rpc id=$nats_request_id\n");
    async(nats_request("rpc.lookup", $var(payload), 200), on_reply);
}
route[on_reply] {
    if ($retcode == 1) {
        xlog("L_INFO", "rpc id=$nats_request_id reply=$nats_data()\n");
    } else if ($retcode == -1) {
        xlog("L_WARN", "rpc id=$nats_request_id timed out\n");
    }
}

       Example 1.14. Propagate an inbound SIP X-Trace-Id into the
       NATS RPC
route {
    # Reuse the upstream caller's trace id (if present) so the
    # NATS responder logs the same id the SIP gateway logged.
    if ($hdr(X-Trace-Id) != null) {
        $nats_request_id = $hdr(X-Trace-Id);
    }
    async(nats_request("rpc.lookup", $var(payload), 200), on_reply);
}
route[on_reply] {
    # $nats_request_id still holds the id used on this call --
    # the consume-once flag was cleared when nats_request fired,
    # but the stash still reflects the value that went out.
    xlog("L_INFO", "rpc trace=$nats_request_id reply=$nats_data()\n");
}

1.6. Exported MI Functions

1.6.1. nats_consumer_bind

   Register a consumer handle. Takes a single config parameter: a
   semicolon-separated k=v string. Required keys: id, stream, and
   either durable=<name> or ephemeral=1. Optional keys cover the
   full JetStream pull-consumer matrix: filter, filters,
   deliver_policy, start_seq, start_time, replay_policy,
   ack_policy, ack_wait, max_deliver, backoff, max_ack_pending,
   headers_only, sample_freq, rate_limit, inactive_threshold,
   js_domain, api_prefix, ring_capacity.

   Unknown keys are rejected as configuration errors.

   Example 1.15. Register a durable work-queue consumer
opensips-cli -x mi nats_consumer_bind \
  'id=jobs;stream=WORK;durable=jobs_worker;filter=work.jobs;ack_wait=30s
;max_deliver=5'

1.6.2. nats_consumer_unbind

   Remove a handle by id. The handle is marked retired immediately
   so subsequent lookups miss; the consumer process tears down the
   JetStream subscription on its next iteration, and the registry
   reaper frees the handle once all in-flight ack operations
   drain. nats_consumer_unbind always returns promptly — the
   deferred teardown is invisible to the caller.

   Example 1.16. Unbind a handle
opensips-cli -x mi nats_consumer_unbind id=jobs

1.6.3. nats_consumer_list

   List all registered handles with their bind-time configuration
   and current runtime counters (pulls_requested, msgs_delivered,
   acks, naks, terms, redeliveries, poisoned, fetch_skips_full,
   backpressure_drops, fetch_errors, ring_depth).

   Each handle entry also carries two backoff-state fields that
   surface the worker's ensure_subscription_for_handle() retry
   budget:
     * ensure_failures — consecutive ensure-subscription failures.
       Zero on a healthy handle; non-zero while the worker is in
       backoff after the broker rejected js_AddConsumer /
       js_PullSubscribe (e.g. the broker-side durable was deleted
       out from under OpenSIPS, or the underlying stream is
       missing). The next failed retry would push the value to
       seven, at which point the backoff saturates at the 60 s cap
       and a one-shot WARN names the handle.
     * ensure_next_retry_at — unix timestamp (CLOCK_REALTIME
       seconds) before which the worker will skip this handle's
       reconcile tick. Zero means "retry on the next tick".

   Both fields reset to zero on the first successful resubscribe;
   a corresponding INFO ("recovered after N failed ensure
   attempt(s)") fires once per recovery edge so log forwarders can
   tell wedge from recovery without polling.

1.6.4. nats_consumer_health

   Liveness snapshot of the dedicated consumer process. Intended
   for external watchdogs (Prometheus exporters, Nagios checks,
   etc.) -- a wedged or crashed consumer leaves SIP workers
   blocked on the per-handle SHM ring's eventfd with no other
   observable signal.

   Returns a JSON object:
     * tick — monotonic loop-iteration counter incremented once
       per consumer-loop pass.
     * consumer_pid — PID of the consumer process.
     * last_tick_ms_ago — Milliseconds since the last tick
       (CLOCK_MONOTONIC).
     * stale — "true" when last_tick_ms_ago exceeds 5000 ms (more
       than five times the loop's 1 s upper-wait bound) or no tick
       has been observed yet.

   Example 1.17. Poll consumer health from opensips-cli
$ opensips-cli -x mi nats_consumer_health
{
    "tick": 12943,
    "consumer_pid": 4711,
    "last_tick_ms_ago": 821,
    "stale": "false"
}

1.6.5. nats_consumer_stats

   One flat JSON object aggregating the observability counters an
   operator needs to spot back-pressure and IPC saturation. Safe
   to call from the attendant/MI process: the counters live in SHM
   allocated pre-fork.
     * handles, ring_depth / ring_capacity — bound handle count
       and ring occupancy summed across handles.
     * msgs_delivered, pulls_requested, acks, naks, terms,
       redeliveries, poisoned — lifetime delivery/ack totals
       (poisoned counts messages terminated by the
       poison_max_deliver backstop).
     * fetch_skips_full — Fetches skipped because a ring was full
       (flow control, no data loss); backpressure_drops — messages
       fetched but deferred (the broker redelivers); fetch_errors
       — Fetch calls returning a hard error.
     * ack_ipc_depth / ack_ipc_enqueued / ack_ipc_drained /
       ack_ipc_dropped — the worker-to-consumer ack queue: current
       depth plus lifetime totals. A climbing depth or any drops
       mean the consumer process is not draining acks fast enough.
     * rpc_ipc_depth / rpc_ipc_enqueued / rpc_ipc_drained /
       rpc_ipc_dropped — same fields for the async-RPC request
       queue, plus rpc_slot_orphans_reaped (slots reclaimed after
       their worker died).
     * rpc_slots_inflight / rpc_slots_total — async-RPC slot-pool
       occupancy; inflight pinned at total means new nats_request
       calls return -5 (pool full).

   Example 1.18. Poll aggregate consumer stats
$ opensips-cli -x mi nats_consumer_stats
{
    "handles": 2,
    "ring_depth": 0,
    "ring_capacity": 2048,
    "msgs_delivered": 15024,
    "pulls_requested": 15060,
    "acks": 15024,
    "naks": 0,
    "terms": 0,
    "redeliveries": 3,
    "poisoned": 0,
    "fetch_skips_full": 0,
    "backpressure_drops": 0,
    "fetch_errors": 0,
    "ack_ipc_depth": 0,
    "ack_ipc_enqueued": 15024,
    "ack_ipc_drained": 15024,
    "ack_ipc_dropped": 0,
    "rpc_ipc_depth": 0,
    "rpc_ipc_enqueued": 240,
    "rpc_ipc_drained": 240,
    "rpc_ipc_dropped": 0,
    "rpc_slot_orphans_reaped": 0,
    "rpc_slots_inflight": 1,
    "rpc_slots_total": 64
}

1.7. Usage Patterns

1.7.1. Durable Work Queue

   Two or more OpenSIPS instances binding the same durable name on
   the same stream load-balance deliveries via JetStream's
   consumer machinery. No duplicates unless nats_nak()/ack_wait
   expiry triggers a redelivery.

   Example 1.19. startup_route + timer_route drain loop
startup_route {
    nats_consumer_bind(
        "id=jobs;stream=WORK;durable=jobs_worker;"
        "filter=work.jobs;ack_wait=30s;max_deliver=5");
}

timer_route[drain, 1] {
    while (nats_fetch("jobs", 250) > 0) {
        xlog("L_INFO", "job $nats_seq: $nats_data\n");
        nats_ack_next();
    }
}

1.7.2. Ephemeral Advisory Subscriber

   JetStream advisories ($JS.EVENT.ADVISORY.>) are a natural fit
   for an ephemeral consumer — the subscription lives only while
   OpenSIPS does, and inactive_threshold keeps the broker tidy if
   the process dies unexpectedly.

   Example 1.20. Subscribe to max-delivery advisories
startup_route {
    nats_consumer_bind(
        "id=dlq;stream=_SYS_JS;ephemeral=1;"
        "filter=$JS.EVENT.ADVISORY.MAX_DELIVERIES.>;"
        "inactive_threshold=5m");
}

timer_route[check_dlq, 5] {
    while (nats_fetch("dlq", 100) > 0) {
        xlog("L_ALERT", "dead letter: $nats_subject $nats_data\n");
        nats_ack();
    }
}

1.7.3. Request / Reply

   The responder side binds a durable consumer on a stream
   covering the request subject; the requester side calls
   nats_request() from a timer_route or startup_route.

   Example 1.21. Two-route RPC on the same instance
startup_route {
    nats_consumer_bind(
        "id=rpc_srv;stream=RPC;durable=srv;"
        "filter=rpc.call;ack_wait=5s");
}

timer_route[rpc_srv, 1] {
    while (nats_fetch("rpc_srv", 100) > 0) {
        nats_hdr_set("X-Trace-Id", "$nats_hdr(X-Trace-Id)");
        if (nats_reply("echo: $nats_data"))
            nats_ack();
        else
            nats_nak();
    }
}

timer_route[rpc_cli, 5] {
    if (nats_request("rpc.call", "ping", 2000))
        xlog("L_INFO", "reply: $nats_data\n");
}

